Old thread: >>>>891740297

>>> The one link to rule them all <<<
rentry.org/sd-mashup
^ almost everything you will need is linked here, for beginners and advanced users.

>> Quick and easy Jewgle Colab running the latest Web UI<<
colab.research.google.com/github/TheLastBen/fast-stable-diffusion/blob/main/fast_stable_diffusion_AUTOMATIC1111.ipynb
^ Command-line arguments already set for the best experience, includes a VAE, literally idiot proof, specify a path to your models if you wish, just click the play button to run each cell, and click the gradio link in the final output.

>> Washed out colors? Get a VAE <<
The "one link to rule them all" above has some in the models link here rentry.org/sdmodels
^place them in the VAE folder for webui, then you can select one in the settings tab. Or, for older versions or different tools, put them in the same folder as your models, renaming it to the model of your choice but instead of .ckpt make it .vae.pt
For example:
Model: MoistMix.safetensors
VAE: MoistMix.vae.pt
You could also just specify the VAE to use in cmd line arguments by adding "--vae-path [path to VAE]"
Also, not all VAE's are the same, some alter colors, some help with generating hands.

>> Getting empty black images? <<
Add this to your command-line arguments "--no-half-vae"

>>> More useful info <<<
github.com/AUTOMATIC1111/stable-diffusion-webui/wiki
Fyi, Web UI treats safetensor models the same as ckpt, you dont have to rename them or anything to use them, and as the name suggests, they are safer and they load faster.
Also I'd just like to recommend that due to bots crawling Gradio links you should secure it with a password if you're not running Web UI locally. Add "--gradio-auth [username]:[password]" to command line arguments.

They seem smart at first because you're tackling crime in what seems like an efficient manner based on scientific observation. It just turns out to be stupid because human nature gets in the way.

As for the generals, no country has a monopoly of good or bad generals. It comes down to incentives. A big problem Russia has is that generals are only accountable for what they've been told. So, when their subordinates give them incorrect reports, they just run with it since they don't get held to account for the accuracy of their subordinates' intel. But what can they do? If they try to get better information, then they'll get blamed for fucking things up.

In the United States it used to be where you were only guilty for unintentionally harming another person if you were neglegent or reckless. So factory owners and others in positions of power would just fire or avoid anyone who would point out safety problems. That way they wouldn't be liable in court if someone got injured or killed. Then the Johnstown flood happened and the American legal system changed to one that considers you liable for things you don't know and makes it your responsibility to make sure you're not harming others. So if you sell contaminated food, you can get arrested because you didn't find out if it was safe.

Russian generals are like American factory owners in the pre-Johnstown flood era. They're not held to account for what they don't know. As a result, they like to get bad intel and a lot of it to cover their asses. Russia needs to learn from America and hold their generals responsible for actually figuring out what's really going on on the battlefield.

This one's easier to practice with. It's a winged horse. Notice how the image is divided into stripes of a repeating pattern? You're trying to cross or diverge your eyes so that one double images of the pattern lines up with the adjacent one in what your other eye is seeing. When you see normally, both eyes point at the same place in the pattern and it just looks like a flat screen. But if you make them see the image offset from each other by 1 pattern width, you see a 3D image that's represented by how the copies of the pattern have parts of them shifted left or right. Like how the stripes sort of converge toward the bottom of the image -- this is a floor coming out toward you when you view it right.

If you diverge or cross your eyes much further, by the whole width of the frame, you can view side-by-side 3D images or videos without needing a headset. Viewing it smaller makes it easier since you don't have to cross or diverge as much.
